description:
Starring: Alan Scott (as Green Lantern) and Doiby Dickles.

Green Lantern was published by DC Comics, then known as National Periodical Publications, lasting for 38 issues from 1941 until 1949. Green Lantern had previously made is debut in the anthology series, All-American Comics, beginning with issue #16 and was popular enough to feature in his own magazine. In addition to the regular Green Lantern features, back-up stories included regular strips such as Hop Harrigan and Mutt & Jeff. Alan Scott also acquired a pet dog, named Streak, that would sometimes feature on the main cover.

Collected Editions:

  • Golden Age Green Lantern Archives #1
  • Golden Age Green Lantern Archives #2
name: Green Lantern

description:
Series of trade paperbacks collecting the Unity event, a company-wide crossover and storyline about time travel set in The Lost Land (from Turok). Unity was told in all eight ongoing titles of Valiant comics in 1992 along with two bookend issues - Unity #0 - Chapter 1: Ends of the Earth and Unity #1 - Unity Chapter 18: Until the End of Time. The event was plotted by Jim Shooter.

Unity #0 was given away in stores with a cover date of July 1992. The story line was continued in each ongoing title (twice) and was concluded in Unity #1.

The order of the Unity chapters:

  • Chapter 1: Unity #0
  • Chapter 2: Eternal Warrior #1
  • Chapter 3: Archer & Armstrong #1
  • Chapter 4: Magnus #15
  • Chapter 5: X-O Manowar #7
  • Chapter 6: Shadowman #4
  • Chapter 7: Rai #6
  • Chapter 8: Harbinger #8
  • Chapter 9: Solar #12
  • Chapter 10: Eternal Warrior #2
  • Chapter 11: Archer & Armstrong #2
  • Chapter 12: Magnus #16
  • Chapter 13: X-O Manowar #8
  • Chapter 14: Shadowman #5
  • Chapter 15: Rai #7
  • Chapter 16: Harbinger #9
  • Chapter 17: Solar #13
  • Chapter 18: Unity #1

Almost three years later Valiant published another chapter (#19) in the one-shot Unity: The Lost Chapter #1.

Note: Valiant's Unity is not to be confused with Acclaim's Unity 2000 that was also plotted by Jim Shooter. A failed attempt to combing the continuity of both universes (VH-1 and VH-2).
name: Unity Saga
